# Your child and ELSA

If your child is attending a preschool, kindergarten or early learning centre in the ELSA pilot, you may be wondering what this means for your family.

ELSA is a new program designed to help children explore science, technology, engineering and mathematics (STEM). It uses a mix of hands-on and digital activities. The digital activities are delivered via ELSA apps for children, which are available at the preschool on iPad and/or Android tablets. 

## ELSA apps 

ELSA apps go beyond the screen to encourage active play and act as a springboard for children to explore the natural world. The apps encourage children to ask questions, make predictions, experiment, and reflect on what happened and why. 

Each child in the pilot will use the ELSA apps for a maximum of 40 minutes per week (broken up into smaller sessions). The pilot aims to minimise screen time while maximising learning outcomes. 

## Why STEM practices are important

Our ELSA apps allow children to explore STEM practices. STEM practices are the ideas, methods and values that underpin STEM. They are important because they help children develop strong skills and values that are useful later in life, such as:
* problem solving
* communication
* creativity
* curiosity

## ELSA and the Early Years Learning Framework

ELSA is aligned with the Early Years Learning Framework (EYLF). This framework supports and enhances young children's learning from birth to five years of age, as well as their transition to school.

## What will the ELSA pilot look like?

Preschools are customising ELSA activities to meet the needs of families in their community. So the ELSA pilot will look different in different environments. Generally, though, you can expect that your child will interact with ELSA as part of their daily play and learning. 

The ELSA pilot moves through three steps to introduce STEM concepts to children: experience, represent, apply.  

### Step 1: Experience

Firstly, children will experience STEM concepts. During this stage educators will help your child notice STEM concepts while they are playing - for example, while building towers with blocks or collecting seed pods outside. Educators will also prepare and direct fun experiences for your child that introduce STEM concepts.  

### Step 2: Represent

After these hands-on experiences, your child will have a chance to represent their ideas on an ELSA app. The app's educational games encourage them to do things like create colourful patterns and sort healthy food by shape, size, or another attribute they choose. 

Activities on the apps have been designed for children to play together, communicate, and engage with the world around them. They can take photos and be creative as they play. 

