### Step 3: Apply

Your child can then apply what they learn from the app with more hands-on activities. They may find new ways to express new ideas, and be inspired to do things differently with the ideas they have developed. 

## Talk about ELSA 

Talk to your child about how they are finding ELSA. As ELSA is still in development, we would love to hear your feedback, good or bad. The 2018 pilot is intended to find ways to improve ELSA, so feel free to share your experiences of the pilot with us. 

You can contact us at team@elsa.edu.au or call 1800 931 042. Alternatively, you can fill out an anonymous survey. 

Ways to be involved with ELSA

ELSA is what you make it. Our apps and activities are designed for you to create alongside your preschool. 

For the first three months of 2018, ELSA is focusing on patterns and relationships. 

Here are some ways you can connect with your preschool:
* Bring in a collection of shells, rocks or other objects for children to observe and sort.
* Make bunting to hang around the preschool that has a sequenced pattern of colours. One of the ELSA activities is about creating patterns to put up around a cubby house. 
* Make up a dance at home that has a pattern to it. For example: clap, clap, stomp, clap, clap stomp. Or clap, spin, clap, clap, spin clap. It can be any pattern and action you want. Your child can then do the dance with friends at preschool. The educator can even lead the whole class in a dance pattern activity. 

Talk to your educator about how you can be involved in bringing ELSA to life.
